 Erdõl und Kohle., Hamburg 16: 478-82, 1963. — From the regressive Devonian Curuá Group in the Amazon Basin, subdivided by Ludwig into 7 fades units with spedal consideration of the sedimentary minor internal structures, 22 shale samples of the lower 4 fades units were studied through mineralogical, petrological, and geochemical methods. The shales of the Fades Unit I, deposited in the deepest bathyal region of the marine basin under anaerobe conditions, are laminated and show a gamma radiation, contents of organic matter, sulphur, pyrite, trace elements, and heavy metals higher as compared with the other studied fades units. According to the thermo-reactions of the organic substances, the shales of the Unit I belong to the “oil-type” and are supposed to be oil source rocks. - To a smaller extent, this also applies to the shales of the Fades Unit II, which were deposited in a shallower bathyal area with occasional currents and, under anaerobe, in part somewhat aerobe conditions. ■ The shales of the Facies Units III and IV cannot be regarded as oil source rocks. They contain virtually no pyrite and were deposited in an in-jraneritic region of the basin under predominantly aerobe conditions. Carboniferous substances observed, and degree of coalification in the bituminous shales. The bitumen, soluble in predpitation naphtha, shows very different viscosities. It consists of oil with high viscosity, vaseline-like and pastelike bitumen, and brittle solid bitumen. The solvent extract corresponds to a solid paraffin oil, poor in asphalt, with only poorly marked montan wax-like resin-wax characteristics. The present mineralogical, petrological, and geochemical residts verify the facies interpretations of the Lower and, Middle Curuá Formations by Ludwig, which were based on sedimentological studies. ■ (Originais recebidos em 21-VDI-67.) Fig. 10 — Mapa de subafloramento do Siluriano e Devoniano na Bacia do médio e baixo Amazonas, com a situação das perfurações
